      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In your Aug. 2 news article about the nominating petition battles at the New York Board of Elections, you cite my observation that these contests are waged ''without involving the voters.'' Of course, I view this disapprovingly.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>In your Aug. 2 news article about the nominating petition battles at the New York Board of Elections, you cite my observation that these contests are waged ''without involving the voters.'' Of course, I view this disapprovingly.</p>
        <p>For 20 years I have advocated alternative means for access to the ballot so that elections are open and democratic. Candidates should be able to spend all their time and resources campaigning rather than defending the bona fides of every signature on their petitions.</p>
        <p>JERRY H. GOLDFEDER  New York, Aug. 2, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is an election lawyer.</p>
      </block>
